title: Shame On You
extra:
From an early age I have always been driven by the goal to achieve as much as I possibly could. My first attempt was to get to drama school by the age of twenty one, my second goal was to be in a film by twenty five, the final achievement I set myself was to retire from normal jobs by thirty; I suppose two out of three ain’t bad!
I am a professional actor and since leaving drama school my roles have been various, which I’m extremely lucky to have accomplished. They range from comedy (Roland Burrell) in Little Britain to Big John in the British gangster movie starring Clive Owen I’ll sleep when I’m dead. My last role was in the 2013 Hollywood blockbuster Red 2 were I had the opportunity to work alongside Helen Mirren.
However I also have a calling for music. I find singing a form of pure escapism from the mundane nine to five, I know you feel me on that one. During my youth my Granddad used to play many songs to me as we talked about many a subject, what I didn’t realise was while I was hearing the music I must have been subconsciously listening too. As I became older and preparing myself for drama school the urge to become a singer grew with it. My main early influences were Stevie Wonder, Billy Holiday, Fats Waller,  Kate Bush, Peter Tosh, Bob Marley, Jimi Hendrix, Prince, James Brown. My later influences are Dwele, Jill Scott, Muddy Waters, Buddy Guy, Nick Drake, Eric Roberson , and is still forever growing. As you can see I’ve always had mad love for music.
My musical credits are still in the making and I sang at Glastonbury Music festival last year and have just been asked back. I’ve also appeared on an unforscene album called Return of the Wob and most weekends entertain the local crowds with my various bands at live music venues around the UK mainly my home town Bristol and London.
As you can see I am an all rounded performing artist who is hard working and never afraid to an accept a challenge, My strength lye in performance i have the ability to immerse myself into a song not just singing it but bring life to it so the audience can relate to something that becomes real again, almost tangible.
My passion for singing is equal to my love for performing, I believe to truly make it as a successful singer you don't only have to be able to sing but also be equal to being a great actor/performer.

Appreciate your time,

Kirris

title: At Eight in a Spanish Bar
extra:
PRESS RELEASE **

Shibuya Crossings – DOYA (Depend On Your Alter-Ego)
Released through Typically Magic Records June 13th

Sometimes it’s hard to know what genre a band fits into or what criteria to use to make such a decision. What exactly defines Alt or Indie, Rock, Indie Rock or Indie Pop for that matter? Shibuya Crossings opt to forget about all this and just make music that feels right and it’s a hell of a refreshing choice to have made. Formed in ’06, Shibuya Crossings sound like a band unconcerned with the trivialities of the more fashionable end of the indie spectrum.

Depend On Your Alter Ego (or DOYA for short) is a sophomore album that ebbs and flows like the Thames that runs through Shibuya Crossings’ adopted London. From the concise, effortless indie-cool of opener (and current single) 'At Eight In A Spanish Bar', past the gloriously sun-kissed riff party If 'It Isn’t Getting Better' right up to the genuinely affecting climax 'A Wonder Inside' the trio marshal exactly what it feels lik

title: Take It Out On Me
extra:
Release Date: Fri 15th October 2010

Full bio available at http://www.shibuyacrossings.com/PR/ShibuyaCrossings-TakeItOutOnMe-Released151010.pdf

Contact: Declan Harrington (Typically Magic Records) 07796693984, info@shibuyacrossings.com

Track already been picked up by Rory McConnell on BBC Introducing, Single launch party at Rhythm Factory, 16-18 Whitechapel Rd., London E1 1EW on Thursday 14th October

--

Indie Rock outfit Shibuya Crossings are set to release their brand new single 'Take It Out On Me' on October 15th via Typically Magic Records. The first single to be taken from their highly anticipated second album 'DOYA (Depend On Your Alter-ego)' showcases a progressive musical and lyrical departure from their 2007 debut 'Songs For Lovesick Teenagers'.
Although nearly 3 years since their last release, the band haven't lost their knack for catchy hooks and melodies. The three and a half minute roller coaster that is 'Take It Out On Me' delivers a tasty concoction of electric disco beats, funky bass lines and a thumping guitar driven chorus.
'It's a song about paranoia, looking over your shoulder all the time' says singer, guitarist Declan Harrington, 'in the case of this song I think that paranoia could be justifi ed, or maybe it's all in the subject's head - you could read it both ways I guess'.
In contrast to the dark lyrical theme, the music itself comes across as upbeat in mood.
The verses are disco-esque, bringing Blondie and Franz Ferdinand to mind, while the chorus with its crunching guitars throws you slap bang into mosh pit territory, reminiscent of Super Furry Animals and Weezer.
The closing chorus of the song is even bigger again, helped by a frantic honky tonk piano and addictive sing-along vocals.

title: Blue Dream
extra:
Nathan VanderVoort is a multi-talented, young, energetic, enthusiastic and passionate musician based out of Arizona. His writing styles are anywhere from Rock to Reggae to Country and Folk / Acoustic music. Nate is currently seeking a Writing/Publishing deal for his songwriting abilities, as well as a distribution / record deal for his top-notch vocal & guitar playing skills.

Nate's musical talents range from being a vocalist, multi-instrumentalist (including guitar, keys, bass, drums and percussion), song writer / composer, lyricist as well as an accomplished audio engineer with 10+ years of experience and education in sound and performing. Biggest musical influences are DMB, Goo Goo Dolls, Matchbox 20, Zac Brown Band, Bruno Mars, Sublime, Train, BuckCherry and Oasis.

Nathan currently makes a living performing with the Nate Williams Band, and has gained thousands of fans not only in Arizona, but all over the US because of his huge exposure performing 5-7 shows per week! Playing live, Nate is accompanied live by some of the most talented musicians that Phoenix has to offer - always putting on a professional show - every night!

There is nothing held back, whether in the studio, on stage, on air, or on camera - If anyone out there deserves an opportunity to make it in the Music Industry - this is the Guy. He has devoted the last 15 years of his life to his craft - and isn't backing down any time soon!

For more information, or to contact Nathan, please visit www.NateWilliamsBand.com and use the contact information for his Management. Thanks for listening, we hope to hear from you!

title: I Am Only Human
extra:
I am only human, go ahead check my DNA
I’m not tryin’ to make excuses, but you know that’s what they say.
I won’t blame my friends, won’t blame the alcohol.
‘Cause I am only human, sometimes I trip and fall.
I am only human, that’s as far as I evolved.
Gonna take a million years until we have this problem solved.
You can call it instinct, you can call it nature’s law.
I am only human and that’s my biggest flaw.
Chorus:

I am only human, I can make a mistake.
I am only human, can’t you give me a break?
She don’t mean nothin’, don’t mean nothin’ to me.
I just gave her a little kiss, that-I-wish you didn’t see.
Yeah I know I wasn’t thinkin’, And I guess I was wrong.
Now I’m askin’ you to comeback, you’ve been gone way too long.
I don’t know how this happens.
Must be in my genes.
I got no explanation
‘Cept I’m just one of those human beings.
I am only human, that’s what my momma told me
Then I read it in a book and that pretty much sold me
I am sorry there ain’t more proof, you have to take my word
That I’ve always been human since my first day occured.
I am only human, ask anyone that knows.
From the top of my head, all the way down to my toes.
Sometimes I wonder if I can’t help the way I act.
‘Cause I am only human and that’s a natural fact.
Chorus: repeat first verse and first two lines of chorus and out

title: Be4me
extra:
Penticton-born, North Vancouver-based Robin Younge is a singer, songwriter and guitarist who performs under the moniker of Clouds of Analog.
Inspired and influenced by the likes of Peter Gabriel, Nine Inch Nails and Emmylou Harris, Younge is set to introduce himself with the release of his first full-length album, The Funeral March, on March 13, 2012.
Produced in Vancouver by up-and-comer Martin Acosta and mixed by Delwyn Brooks (Bif Naked, Holly McNarland) The Funeral March is a collection of songs based on the emotional stages of grief.  The first single, “Lately”, focuses on the battle with one’s ego and how it is used to protect oneself from getting hurt, which inevitably leads to the inability to truly enjoy the gifts that come one’s way.
Having spent most of his life listening to music as a source of comfort and therapy, Younge has always been determined to write and perform his own. 
“My entire life, I’ve wanted to write the music that I’m writing right now.  This is my path and although it has been a long and challenging one, there’s nothing else that I see myself doing."

title: Holy Now Again
extra:
Written by David JetBlackhorse and Mark Montague January 10th, 2012
At The Chop Shop, 7000 feet in the air,
land of enchantment, new mexico, usa, santa fe.
3 days after JetBlackhorse broke on through to the other side.

Holy Now Again

Only Life endangers death, and there is nothing that
will stay the same from the beating of all hearts
into the cosmic skies above
Ideas thick like bricks that strangle the mind
into this moment
clouds of lust inside my soul
secret memories I behold
ancient mysteries do unfold
is only now again
It's Holy Now Again

I don't feel alone or the pain anymore,
now that i've found my way back home
I haven't passed away
I'm just tuned to another vibration
you know i'm with you
that's everything to me

it's like that movie... you know....
"Everything's Karate"
Now is what we have been given
when you wake up tomorrow in the future
it will only be only now again
it's Holy Now Again
the silence in my mind was the only place that
I could not hide the drops of gold
that are in our veins they're always there
they're what remains
the future in the past, the same
it's only now again

I don't feel alone or the weight of the stone
like a dog I found the place to bury my bone
I haven't passed away
I'm just tuned to another vibration
you know i'm with you
that's everything to me

ok, gotta have a little dark side
in my life i never ever felt such misery, physically
emotionally, financially, and summarily, never ever, fuck this feeling fuck this
feeling, fuck it fuck it
I had been thinking of the disapperance of my life
I have to either pay the price or keep quiet
I don't want to hang that legacy on my kids
or for anyone else's pleasure
why was everything so hard man?
well, i know now, without the hard there is no easy

the days turn into months and the months turn into years
and the years turn into only now again
it's Holy Now Again
you've fallen down get up again
get it? within, get off again
you're in you're out?
it all depends
still it's only now again
It's Holy Now Again

title: Soundtrack / Easy Listening
extra:
Jon Purdey is a dynamic composer who specializes in everything from epic Dramatic and Orchestral cues to modern Trance, Dance, Dubstep, Hip Hop, Rock, Folk, Ambient, and New Age music.

He's scored a variety of Film, TV, and corporate projects, including a theme for the 2013 Audi and Kia reveals. Some other credits include - Fox Sports, Americas Next Top Model, Toddlers & Tiaras, Vice, Alien Encounters, Best Thing I Ever Made, Auction Kings, iGenius: How Steve Jobs Changed the World, NY Ink, Last Call with Carson Daly, Mob Wives, #Rich Kids of Beverly Hills, Annie: It’s a Hard Knock Life, Sins & Secrets, Futurescape, Eyewitness War, Homicide Hunter, Canadian Police Commercial & I Almost Got Away With It.

Love Strikes
extra:
J.M. Long is a singer-songwriter and musician based out of Los Angeles, CA. His music can best be described as melodic indie-rock with faint splashes of folk. Hailing from artsy Portland, OR, he has the versatility of performing in a full-blown rock concert with his four-piece band or playing a stripped down solo performance in an intimate setting with nothing but an acoustic guitar and cappuccino.

Before moving to Los Angeles in the fall of 2011, Long recorded and performed around the northwest with a multitude of composers and musicians as both a front man (vocals, keys, guitar), backing musician (keys, guitar, bass), and orchestra member (2nd violin). He was also privileged to take four years of guitar, performance and production classes from legendary guitarist and producer Tim Ellis (co-owner of Kung Fu Bakery Recording Studio). Currently, he is preparing to perform at the House of Blues (Sunset Strip) to promote his debut EP Torn and Restored, which was released this spring, along with a music video for the single “Love Strikes”.

title: Free
extra:
Angela Mukul (pronounced McCool) is an upbeat, pop singer-songwriter who describes her sound as “pop with a touch of soul”. She’s been performing live as a solo artist for over 9 years, in addition to recording in studio on both her own tracks and those of others.

Most recently, Angela released her debut EP Free containing 6 self-written songs and the music video for I’d Rather Be Single, the first single off her EP.
Just last year, Angela broadcast her talents on the CW Network’s new music competition show: The NEXT where she was mentored by the Queen of Latin Pop herself: Gloria Estefan. Angela’s live television performance can be viewed online and a full-length version of the song she performed on the show, You And I-Lady Gaga, can be found on iTunes.

Angela’s fan base continues to rapidly grow and she now has fans in over 20 countries. As a songwriter, she has been a finalist in national and international songwriting competitions. Writing constantly, the messages within her songwriting focus on: love, optimism and empowerment. Undoubtedly an artist who knows exactly what she stands for, Angela seeks to shine light on the world through her one true passion: music.

extra:
Janie M is a 'passionate' songwriter from Melbourne Australia with a long association to the music industry she states her passion began with the great 'Glam' artists of the 1970s. "I can relate to their messages which were defined in their music in a clear and punchy way !" "Those artists lived hard and played hard !" When asked about her musical experience Janie M states with alot of energy " I was a participant in the 2009 Hollywood 'Rock N Roll Fantasy Camp' as a backup singer, alongside Todd Rundgren, Steven Tyler, Steve Lukather (Toto), Kip Winger and the Guns N Roses members." "I was told our band rocked hard at the Whisky A Go Go it was a great learning experience !"
With a band name chosen as the Sunset Strippers, Janie M's sense of humour shined through alongside hard work and efforts at the Rock camp with her other valuable band members !
Janie M has experience in story writing and as a voice over artist, she says her music is trying to come out in many genres through hooks and catchy phrases "We can all relate to a realistic lyric, and Im a great advocate for the Pop, Country and Dance genres!" "The music in my head is keen to say something !"

title: Waiting for September
extra:
His Haircut is a band formed by Spanish songwriter Vera Domínguez, in 2007. After quitting her band “Liquor” she was looking for new musicians to play her electric-folk live, and this is how His Haircut was born. They self-produced a demo in 2009, filmed a video (directed by Irlanda Tambascio & Cucho Ramírez), and gig regularly.

They reached the final of a music contest, and their music has featured in two TV shows, “Fama ¡a Bailar!” and “La Pecera de Eva”, as well as in a movie “Esperando Septiembre” by Tina Olivares, and a short film "Beautiful Obsessions" by Greg Lucas.

Vera also wrote and song main themes for the trilogy of the game “Runaway”. About the name, is only a joke between friends! (Noah & Vera). It was someone else’s idea, a friend told us, and we thought it was funny.

title: Neanderthal
extra: Commenting on video game violence is about as uncool as you can get, but the images that people immerse themselves in of gore, death, and murder is remarkable. It's not just the blowing up your friends in a sci-fi or fantasy setting, where the brutality is cartoonish. But in Grand Theft Auto or Saints Row, you choose a path of sociopathy, randomly killing whoever gets in your way. Are the games entertaining? Definitely. Is it fun to kill people in an imaginary world (that's made to be as realistic as possible) and live out a criminal life? Yep, it certainly is. It's a rush. But that rush we get is because our subconscious isn't good at telling the difference between reality and fantasy, it feels these actions as real. The images, noise, and action that our rational mind says are "just a game" are taken as real by the subconscious. That's why we get the adrenaline from the game. We get to engage our inner caveman, our bestial natures. But is there any kind of psychological price to this devolution? Does spend

title: Neanderthal
extra: Commenting on video game violence is about as uncool as you can get, but the images that people immerse themselves in of gore, death, and murder is remarkable. It's not just the blowing up your friends in a sci-fi or fantasy setting, where the brutality is cartoonish. But in Grand Theft Auto or Saints Row, you choose a path of sociopathy, randomly killing whoever gets in your way. Are the games entertaining? Definitely. Is it fun to kill people in an imaginary world (that's made to be as realistic as possible) and live out a criminal life? Yep, it certainly is. It's a rush. But that rush we get is because our subconscious isn't good at telling the difference between reality and fantasy, it feels these actions as real. The images, noise, and action that our rational mind says are "just a game" are taken as real by the subconscious. That's why we get the adrenaline from the game. We get to engage our inner caveman, our bestial natures. But is there any kind of psychological price to this devolution? Does spend
